pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an understanding that improvement in a high performing school is likely to be incremental and less significant than in a poor performing school</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that there was never an expectation to sponsor</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that support is happening but may not be well </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">advertised in a local community for obvious reasons.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To encourage sponsorship there needs to be some financial incentive in order to release capacity.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Another encouragement would be to make working with other schools part of the accountability framework.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To secure progress of disadvantaged pupils it should be more rigotously looked at by OFSTED.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Local Authorities hamper the process of academy conversion and this needs </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">addressing.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The DfE needs better internal communication as well as better </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">communication with OFSTED to inform its decisions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Free Schools should be a response to demographic need and/or local underperformance. In the latter case action also needs to be taken to address that underperformance.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The role of the Regional Schools Commissioners needs to be clarified and linked to </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the OFSTED Regional Directors. Together, sharing information and with effective communication, they should provide the system for identifying schools needing support and sc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hools with capacity to support.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Local Authorities should not have a role in school monitoring and improvement. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The regional structures of OFSTED and the Schools Commissioners could provide what is required. However, light-touch and leave successful s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">chools to be autonomous.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Chains need to be limited in size and geographical spread.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Preference for smaller local chains.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Chains need to be inspected together.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Governance is an issue throughout the system. There needs to be a move from the stakeholder </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">model to a skills based model.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is appropriate for a primary school to become an academy. However:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Schools should be above a certain size to be effective as an academy</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Below that size there should be an expectation that they are in a formal group of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">schools</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Grouping should be encouraged and incentivized.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Alternatives to sponsorship for failing primary schools would be:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A requirement to join a Multi-Academy Trust</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A requirement to work with HMI.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A school closure and amalgamation – either as a single</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> school or in a hard federation.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 13pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 13pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 13pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">FASNA’s Report</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.71pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of academisation in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children, and what further steps should be taken within the academies system to bring about a transformational imp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">act on student </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">outcomes</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The debate about the academisation of our schools is marred by ill-founded judgements with no basis in evidence and often with expectations of academies whi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ch have been changed mid-stream.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The early sponsor academies were specifically</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> established to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> address under-performance in mainly urban areas with high levels of deprivation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">With a hard-edged arrangement with a sponsor, extra funding and a clear brief to raise standards and address social disadvantage, their purpose was well articu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lated. Obvious</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly, as they have been in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">existence for up to ten years </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">there is good evidence to assess their impact and i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n poor performing schools large gains in pupil outcomes are possible.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On the other hand, converter academies have only come into existe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nce over the last three years. There is not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">yet </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">longitudinal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> evidence base to make sweeping judgements about the “system”. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is misjudged or even willful</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to compare the impact of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sponsor and converter academies at this stage.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Also, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">converter academie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">were, initially ‘Outstanding’ Schools and therefore any gains in pupil performance were likely to be incremental and therefore appear less </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">significant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is a factor to be taken into consideration.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The criteria set for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">converter academies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">was that th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ey should ‘support’ other schools. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The recent expectation that this should translate into ensuring that other schools have their outcomes improved is a sleight of hand. Firstly, it was not made an explicit expectation. Secondly, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">no</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-one has monitored what s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">chools are doing in this regard and the impact therefore cannot be known.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Thirdly, s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">upport being given </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is likely to be discreet so as not to undermine the voluntary recipient.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Evidence would seem to indicate that leaders of converter academies have been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">successful in maintaining and improving outcomes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of all pupils </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of disadvantaged pupils </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in their own schools.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In order for academies to have a transformational impact beyond their own schools there needs to be an explicit demand made of them to do so. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The current sponsorship programme is a means to achieve this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. One means of securing this is by providing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the incentive of extra-funding to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">secure capacity. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Without this, academies will shy away from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">volunteering to sponsor for fear</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that capacity issues wil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l lead negatively impact on their own performance.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">OFSTED need to take into account the impact of working with other schools when reaching a judgement on the supporting school.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Another mechanism would be to make working with other schools part of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">accountability framework.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 13pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To secure the progress of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disadvantaged pupils OFSTED could beef up </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Inspection Framework looking at the measurement of the progress of groups – such as FSM, and the spending of the Pupil Premium.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 13pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.71pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The process for approving, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">compelling and establishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsors;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Too often the process is hampered by Local Authorities standing in the way.  For example Redcar &amp; Cleveland currently want to charge legal fees for schools converting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, even if they already buy in to the LA service. They also insist a school must become a cheque-book school for a ‘few months’ before they can become a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n academy. However, they say that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it takes a year to make the change to become a cheque-book school! Such</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disputes are intended to deter schools from the process.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The DfE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> needs to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have better data to identify schools which meet the criteria for being granted academy status, or being compelled</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to become an academy by being sponsored, or for being a sponsor. C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">urrently it appears that different parts of the DfE, and other arms of the Education Service such as OFSTED, do not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">adequately </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">share information or communicate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">effectively </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with each other. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For Free Schools it is not adequate that there is a demand, there</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> must also be a need demonstrated by either by demographics (too few places) or by failure to provide adequate quality in other schools in the locality. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The DfE needs to have the data to substantiate the case. If not, it appears purely an ideological decis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ion which undermines schools in the area – thus having the unintended consequence of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reducing morale and performance in those schools.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If the latter, there also needs to be a plan to address this – by improving quality to acceptable levels and/or reducing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">places at poor quality schools. Establishing a Free School and leaving it to the market condemns a generation of pupils caught in change.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There needs to be a route by which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">OFSTED can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> inform the DfE where they identify capacity in high performing schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(perhaps through their HMI Good Practise Guides?). It is clear from the HMCI Annual Report released last week that OFSTED have such performance data – LA by LA – thus the DfE could begin to trawl for capacity by starting with OFSTED data.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our experience </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">shows that the DfE academy sponsor unit has no systematic or routine knowledge of where there is capacity in the system. Thus, it is incumbent upon high performing schools to contact them to offer support – it should be the other way round.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 13pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he DfE, should be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">able </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to identify those schools requiring sponsorship and those who may provide the necessary expertise to be sponsors. This is best done in a local area</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 13pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.71pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The role of the Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting failing academi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">es, and how this role will work as the programme expands;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This will surely be via the new Regional Schools Com</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">missioner</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s? They should be the layer scrutinising </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">school performance data, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">OFSTED </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reports</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> etc </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">They would track</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> performance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and then broker</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> suppor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">where required</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="mar